From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases, account for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, physical inactivity, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread awareness of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases met from December 9 to 11 at the Second Global Forum of the Non-Communicable Diseases Alliance in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress achieved.
Although the battle is not over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can push back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet journal, described the NCD community as being in need of "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on preventing NCDs, those seeking to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of HIV/AIDS organizations.
The first letter that the NCD community must take into account is « A », as in activism.
Anyone over the age of 40 surely remembers images of AIDS activists participating in « die-in » demonstrations at scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets and even shut down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
Globally, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make drugs more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the « B » of the HIV/AIDS movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The HIV/AIDS movement was clear on this from the beginning and pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: the HIV/AIDS movements did not take long to realize that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Activists have built links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders within public powers, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The HIV/AIDS movement also understood that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, "D," the determining factor of success, consisted of "drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge."
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make smart decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
MNT are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Commitment - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which advocated the mantra "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates demanded the representation of existing organizations in treating the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply embedded in the HIV/AIDS movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the HIV/AIDS community to gain political leader support.
In particular, access to HIV/AIDS treatments has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the narrative in this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
Another important formulation of the issue for AIDS, a very relevant question for the NCDs movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community worked hard to place more emphasis on people's lifestyle choices, rather than attributing responsibility to the state in providing healthcare and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and gender identity was rooted from the beginning in the DNA of the AIDS fight movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focus of NCD prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
Strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The HIV/AIDS movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCDs movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods for children.
We could continue listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS throughout the alphabet, but we think it is appropriate to end on "H," since human rights provided the answer to AIDS and they should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The HIV/AIDS movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The NCD and HIV/AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
